Package edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.io

Class DefaultParser

java.lang.Object
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.io.Parser
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.io.DefaultParser
public class DefaultParser extends Parser
A parser which defines rules and builders for parsing many kinds of common objects, including problems and logical formulas.

When parsing logical formulas, the following precedence rules are used, from highest precedence to lowest:

  • belief expressions
  • conjunctions
  • disjunctions
  • negations
  • conditionals
  • quantified expressions
  • assignments
  • equal to comparisons
  • not equal to comparisons
  • greater than or equal to comparisons
  • less than or equal to comparisons
  • greater than comparisons
  • less than comparisons
  • type constraints
  • products
  • summations
  • multiplication
  • division
  • addition
  • subtraction
Note that conjunctions and disjunctions have high precedence. If X, Y, and Z are Boolean expressions the string "if(X) Y & Z" will be parsed as "(if(X) Y) & (Z)".
Author:
Stephen G. Ware
